%S A391687 1,0,1,0,2880,328458240
%N A391687 Number of bordered magic squares of order n composed of the numbers from 1 to n^2, counted up to rotations and reflections.
%C A391687 A (concentric) bordered magic square of order n is a magic square in which, after removing the outermost (border) rows and columns, the remaining central (n-2) X (n-2) square is also magic square.
%C A391687 The value a(5)=2880 appears in Kraitchik (1942), pp. 166-170, which discusses bordered magic squares of order 5.
%C A391687 The value a(6)=328458240 is quoted in H. D. Heinz and J. R. Hendricks (2000), pp. 20, who attribute it to J. R. Hendricks (1991, unpublished).
%H A391687 R. Descombes, <a href="https://doi.org/10.4000/bibnum.560">Le Carr√© magique Xi'an</a>, Bibnum, Calcul et informatique (2016).
%H A391687 H. D. Heinz, <a href="http://recmath.org/Magic%20Squares/BookSale.htm">Magic Squares and Related Publications</a>.
%H A391687 H. D. Heinz and J. R. Hendricks, <a href="http://recmath.org/Magic%20Squares/Downloads/Lexicon_Sample.pdf">Magic Square Lexicon: Illustrated</a>. 2000, p. 1-20.
%H A391687 M. Kraitchik, <a href="https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4248642&amp;seq=173">Mathematical Recreations</a>, Dover, 1942, 53-9354, pp 166-170.
%e A391687 a(1)=1: the unique 1 X 1 magic square is trivially bordered.
%e A391687 a(2)=0: no 2 X 2 normal magic square exists.
%e A391687 a(3)=1: the unique 3 X 3 normal magic square is bordered, since removing its outer border leaves a 1 X 1 magic square.
%e A391687 a(4)=0: no bordered normal 4 X 4 magic square exists, since removing the outer border leaves a 2 X 2 array, which cannot be a magic square.
%e A391687 An example of a solution at n=6 is the Xi'an magic square, which is quoted in R. Descombes (2016):
